				},
				"paragraphStyle" : {
					"__type" : "textStyle"
				},
				"string" : "##Control flow"
			},
			{
				"__type" : "textSnippet",
				"children" : {
					"__type" : "snippets",
					"items" : [ ]
				},
				"createEmail" : {
					"__type" : "email",
					"emailString" : "<unknown>"
				},
				"createTime" : {
					"__type" : "time",
					"time" : {
						"__type" : "dateAndTime",
						"dateAndTimeString" : "2026-06-11T11:34:52.677363-05:00"
					}
				},
				"editEmail" : {
					"__type" : "email",
					"emailString" : "<unknown>"
				},
				"editTime" : {
					"__type" : "time",
					"time" : {
						"__type" : "dateAndTime",
						"dateAndTimeString" : "2026-06-15T06:30:00.775239-05:00"
					}
				},
				"uid" : {
					"__type" : "uid",
					"uidString" : "8NWc4AR1StGYdkmziV9dxA=="
				},
				"paragraphStyle" : {
					"__type" : "textStyle"
				},
				"string" : "The order in which nodes are processed can be controlled by where the {{gtMethod:SmaCCRewriteMatchContext>>#continue}}, {{gtMethod:SmaCCRewriteMatchContext>>#processChild:}}, or {{gtMethod:SmaCCRewriteMatchContext>>#processChildren}} messages are sent in the code. Normally, AST nodes are processed from the root to the leaves, but this can be changed. For example, if you add a rewrite rule at the top of the script that simply sends `self processChildren` followed by `self continue`, you can effectively change the top-down traversal into a bottom-up traversal from leaves to root. If the order does not matter, having `self continue` at the end is best, because tail-recursion elimination is performed to keep the stack size down."
			}
		]
